LXIV. The wild fig is even much more efficacious than the fig; a sprig of it also curdles milk into cheese.c It has less milk in it than the cultivated fig. This milk is collected and hardened by pressure, when it is rubbed on meat to keep it sweet. Diluted with vinegar it forms an ingredient of blistering preparations, It relaxes the bowels; with starch it opens the uterus3 with the yolk of egg it promotes menstruation.
